          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Good news: your completion flow already works well — tasks are *moved* to a `completed-tasks` collection, not deleted. That's a natural undo point. The problem is only with **hard deletes** (`$pull` removes the task permanently).\n\nHere's a concrete plan for both unified gestures and backend undo:\n\n---\n\n## Unified Swipe Convention\n\nRight now you have three different swipe systems:\n\n| Component | Left swipe | Right swipe | Down swipe |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| SwipableTaskCard | Complete (green) | 3 buttons (bell, flag, trash) | — |\n| SchedulableTaskCard | Nothing | Delete | — |\n| ReviewTaskCard | Skip | Complete | Delete |\n\n**Proposal: One pattern everywhere**\n\n- **Right swipe = Complete** (positive action, green) — matches natural left-to-right \"done\" mental model\n- **Left swipe = Contextual negative** (red) — delete or skip depending on screen\n- **Drop the down-swipe entirely** in ReviewTaskCard — it conflicts with scrolling and is undiscoverable\n- **Drop the 3-button reveal** on SwipableTaskCard — bell and flag are non-functional (`console.log` only), and the trash is better served by a long-press menu\n\n**Making gestures discoverable:**\n\n1. **First-time peek animation** — On the user's first encounter with a swipeable card, auto-animate it ~40px to the right then back, revealing the green \"Complete\" action behind it. Store a flag in AsyncStorage so it only plays once.\n2. **Subtle edge affordance** — Show a faint colored edge (green right, red left) on cards so users sense there's something behind them. A 2-3px colored border on the card edge is enough.\n3. **Swipe progress label** — You already do this in ReviewTaskCard (show \"done ✓\" / \"skip\" during swipe). Apply this same pattern to SwipableTaskCard and SchedulableTaskCard.\n\n---\n\n## Backend Undo Strategy\n\nYour tasks are hard-deleted with `$pull`, so once gone, they're gone. Here are two approaches, from simplest to most robust:\n\n### Option A: Frontend-delayed delete (simplest, no backend changes)\n\n```\nUser swipes delete\n  → Remove card from UI immediately (optimistic)\n  → Show toast: \"Task deleted · UNDO\" with 5-second timer\n  → Start a 5-second setTimeout\n  → If user taps Undo: re-insert card into local state, cancel the timeout\n  → If timer expires: NOW call DELETE /v1/user/tasks/{category}/{id}\n```\n\n**Pros:** Zero backend work. Undo is instant.\n**Cons:** If the app crashes during the 5-second window, the task reappears on next load (minor inconsistency but no data loss). Doesn't work across devices.\n\n### Option B: Soft delete with backend TTL (more robust)\n\nAdd a `deletedAt` field to the task model:\n\n```go\n// types.go - add to TaskDocument\nDeletedAt *time.Time `bson:\"deletedAt,omitempty\" json:\"deletedAt,omitempty\"`\n```\n\nThen change the delete flow:\n\n1. **`DELETE /tasks/{category}/{id}`** — Instead of `$pull`, set `deletedAt: now()`:\n   ```go\n   bson.M{\"$set\": bson.M{\"tasks.$.deletedAt\": time.Now()}}\n   ```\n\n2. **`POST /tasks/{category}/{id}/restore`** — New endpoint, unsets `deletedAt`:\n   ```go\n   bson.M{\"$unset\": bson.M{\"tasks.$.deletedAt\": \"\"}}\n   ```\n\n3. **Filter soft-deleted tasks from all reads** — Add `\"tasks.deletedAt\": bson.M{\"$exists\": false}` to your aggregation pipelines, or filter in the service layer.\n\n4. **Cron job for permanent cleanup** — Run every hour, `$pull` any task where `deletedAt` is older than 30 minutes (or whatever window you choose). You already have the `$pull` logic, just add a time filter.\n\n5. **Frontend** — Same undo toast UX, but call `/restore` on undo instead of cancelling a timeout.\n\n**Pros:** Works across devices, survives crashes, consistent state.\n**Cons:** Need to update all read queries to exclude soft-deleted tasks.\n\n---\n\n### Same pattern for undo-complete\n\nCompletion already moves tasks to `completed-tasks`. To undo:\n\n1. **`POST /tasks/undo-complete/{id}`** — Find the task in `completed-tasks`, move it back into the original category's task array, decrement `tasks_complete` on the user, and roll back template streak stats.\n2. **Time-window it** — Only allow undo within N minutes of `timeCompleted`, same as your existing `UndoMissedTask` pattern (which already checks a 24-hour window on `lastMissedAt`).\n\nThe frontend undo toast works identically: show it for 5-8 seconds, call the endpoint on tap.\n\n---\n\n**My recommendation:** Start with **Option A** (frontend-delayed delete). It covers 95% of accidental swipes with zero backend work. Add Option B later if you want cross-device consistency or a longer undo window. For undo-complete, you'll need a backend endpoint either way since the task has already been moved to another collection.\n\nWant me to implement any of these?",
