          "text": "Good question. Two reasonable options:\n\n### Option 1: Only latest undoable (current design)\nEach delete gets its own independent 5s timeout. New toast replaces the old one. Previous timeouts fire on schedule — you can only undo the most recent delete.\n\n**Problem:** If you delete 3 tasks in 2 seconds, you can only recover the last one.\n\n### Option 2: Rolling batch with single timer (recommended)\n\nThe `pendingDeletesRef` becomes a `Map<taskId, {task, categoryId, deleteRecurring}>` instead of a single entry:\n\n```\nDelete task A at t=0  → Map: {A}, toast: \"1 task deleted · Undo\", timer: 5s\nDelete task B at t=2  → Map: {A, B}, toast: \"2 tasks deleted · Undo\", RESET timer to 5s\nDelete task C at t=3  → Map: {A, B, C}, toast: \"3 tasks deleted · Undo\", RESET timer to 5s\n\nAt t=8 (5s after last delete): fire all 3 API calls\nOR if Undo tapped: restore all 3 tasks, clear timer\n```\n\n- Each new delete adds to the pending map and **resets** the countdown\n- Toast updates to show count: \"**N** tasks deleted · Undo\"\n- Undo restores **all** pending tasks at once\n- When the timer fires, all pending API calls execute (can use `bulkDeleteTasksAPI` for non-recurring, individual calls for recurring with `deleteRecurring=true`)\n- If any API call fails, only that task is restored to UI\n\nThis matches how Google Keep / Gmail web handle batch undo. It's a small change to the design — just swap the single ref for a Map and reset the timer on each new delete.\n\nWant to go with option 2?",
